<script type="application/ld+json">
{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"Is debt settlement better than bankruptcy?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"For most people with significant unsecured debt, no. Chapter 7 bankruptcy eliminates debt in 3-4 months, costs $1,500-2,500 total, and has no tax consequences. Settlement takes 2-4 years, charges 15-25% of enrolled debt in fees, triggers taxes on forgiven amounts, and only resolves 35-60% of enrolled debts."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Do you have to pay taxes on settled debt?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. Forgiven debt over $600 is reported on IRS Form 1099-C and treated as taxable income. An insolvency exception may apply if your liabilities exceeded your assets at the time of forgiveness. Bankruptcy discharge, by contrast, is specifically excluded from taxable income under IRC Section 108."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How much do settlement companies charge?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Settlement companies typically charge 15-25% of the total enrolled debt. On $50,000 of enrolled debt, that is $7,500-$12,500 in fees. This is separate from the actual settlement payments to creditors and does not include taxes on forgiven debt or accrued interest."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can creditors sue me during settlement?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. There is no legal protection during a settlement program. Creditors can continue to call, send letters, file lawsuits, and garnish wages. Only bankruptcy provides the automatic stay under Section 362, which immediately stops all collection activity."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What if debt settlement does not work?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"You can still file bankruptcy. Many people try settlement first, fail, and then file bankruptcy. Unfortunately, they have spent 1-3 years and thousands in fees before arriving at the solution that would have worked in 3-4 months."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Does settlement hurt your credit more than bankruptcy?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Both damage credit significantly. However, settlement creates ongoing damage over 2-4 years (rolling delinquencies), while bankruptcy is a single event after which you can immediately rebuild. Most Chapter 7 filers recover to 700+ within 2-3 years. Settlement clients often take longer because the damage is more recent and spread over more time."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What percentage of settlement programs actually work?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Industry data suggests that only 35-60% of enrolled debts are successfully settled. Many people drop out of settlement programs before completion because of lawsuits, garnishment, or the financial strain of making escrow payments while creditors continue to add interest and fees. The FTC has taken enforcement actions against settlement companies for misleading success rate claims."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can I settle my debts myself without paying a company?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. You can call creditors directly and negotiate a reduced lump-sum payoff. This eliminates the 15-25% fee charged by settlement companies. Creditors are more likely to settle once an account is significantly delinquent (90-180 days). You may be able to settle for 30-50 cents on the dollar. However, you still face potential lawsuits during the process and tax liability on any forgiven amount over $600."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Do settlement companies tell you about the tax consequences?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Many do not adequately disclose the tax consequences. When a creditor forgives more than $600 of debt, they report it to the IRS on Form 1099-C, and the forgiven amount is treated as taxable income. On $30,000 of forgiven debt, you could owe $5,000-7,000 in additional taxes depending on your bracket. Bankruptcy discharge, by contrast, is specifically excluded from taxable income under IRC Section 108."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What happens to my credit cards during a settlement program?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Settlement companies typically instruct you to stop paying your credit cards entirely. This causes your accounts to go delinquent, then charge off (usually at 180 days). Each month of missed payments adds a negative mark to your credit report. Your credit score may drop 100-200 points during the first few months. Meanwhile, interest and late fees continue to accrue, increasing your total balance even as you save toward settlement offers."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Is there a way to get debt relief without hurting my credit?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No option that reduces or eliminates debt leaves your credit unaffected. A debt management plan (DMP) through a nonprofit credit counseling agency has the smallest credit impact, but you repay 100% of the principal. Debt consolidation loans may not hurt your score if you keep payments current, but you still owe the full amount. Any option that reduces what you owe - settlement or bankruptcy - will affect your credit. The question is how quickly you can rebuild afterward."}}]}
</script>
